# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gas-pak
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The **Ziehl–Neelsen stain**, also known as the **acid-fast stain**, is a bacteriological staining technique used in cytopathology and microbiology to identify acid-fast bacteria under microscopy, particularly members of the *Mycobacterium* genus.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] This staining method was initially introduced by Paul Ehrlich (1854–1915) and subsequently modified by the German bacteriologists Franz Ziehl (1859–1926) and Friedrich Neelsen (1854–1898) during the late 19th century.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] These acid-fast bacteria possess a waxy lipid-rich outer layer that contains high concentrations of mycolic acid, rendering them resistant to conventional staining techniques like the Gram stain.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] After the Ziehl–Neelsen staining procedure using carbol fuchsin, acid-fast bacteria are observable as vivid red or pink rods set against a blue or green background, depending on the specific counterstain used, such as methylene blue or malachite green, respectively.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Non-acid-fast bacteria and other cellular structures will be colored by the counterstain, allowing for clear differentiation.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] A typical AFB stain procedure involves dropping the cells in suspension onto a slide, then air drying the liquid and heat fixing the cells.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] "Acid alcohol" refers to an alcohol (reagent/solvent-grade; often denatured for tax reasons) solution of hydrochloric acid.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The percentage refers to the acid content by volume.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The mechanism of action of the Ziehl–Neelsen stain has long been discussed and is not completely understood.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Historically, it was believed to involve a chemical reaction between the acidic dyes and the cell walls of the bacteria.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The acidity of the dyes was thought to cause them to bind strongly to the lipid-rich cell walls—particularly to mycolic acids—resulting in the selective staining of only those cells that possess a thick, waxy envelope.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] This traditional view held that these cell-wall lipids were responsible for the retention of the primary dye after acid–alcohol decolourisation, explaining the “acid-fast” property of mycobacteria and related organisms.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The Ziehl–Neelsen stain is a two-step staining process.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] In the first step, the tissue is stained with a basic fuchsin solution, which stains all cells pink.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] In the second step, the tissue is incubated in an acid-alcohol solution, which decolourises all cells except for acid-fast cells, which retain the colour and appear red.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The mechanisms by which this colour is produced were historically thought to involve an interaction of basic fuchsin with cell-wall components, creating a stable dye complex responsible for the observed red coloration.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Recent studies have provided a more detailed and experimentally supported interpretation of this process, however alternative hypotheses to the structures stained, including nucleic acids were proposed.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Fluorescence and confocal microscopy show that the primary dyes (carbol fuchsin and auramine O) actually localise to intracellular nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) rather than to the cell wall itself.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] In this updated model, the cell envelope’s role is mainly to prevent the loss of these dyes during acid–alcohol washing, rather than to act as the dye-binding target.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] This intracellular localisation explains the characteristic “beading” pattern observed in Ziehl–Neelsen and fluorescent acid-fast stains, corresponding to the bacterial nucleoids.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Similar nucleic-acid staining patterns are seen in other acid-fast organisms such as *Cryptosporidium*, *Cystoisospora*, and *Schistosoma* spp.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] These findings indicate that acid-fast stains function primarily as nucleic-acid stains whose retention depends on cell-wall integrity rather than direct binding to mycolic acids.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Studies have shown that an AFB stain without a culture has a poor negative predictive value.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] An AFB culture should be performed along with an AFB stain; this has a much higher negative predictive value.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] In anatomic pathology specimens, immunohistochemistry and modifications of Ziehl–Neelsen staining (such as Fite-Faraco staining) have comparable diagnostic utility in identifying *Mycobacterium*.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Both of them are superior to traditional Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Recent evidence suggests that the low sensitivity of acid-fast stains in histologic sections may be partly due to tissue processing rather than bacterial scarcity.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Standard xylene deparaffinization, routinely used in histopathology, damages the lipid-rich envelope of mycobacteria and markedly reduces fluorescence and detectability with both Ziehl–Neelsen and fluorescent stains.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] A solvent-free, heat-based projected hot-air deparaffinization method significantly increased the yield and fluorescence intensity of mycobacteria in formalin-fixed, paraffin-embedded tissues, without compromising tissue morphology.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] These results indicate that the integrity of the mycobacterial cell wall is essential for acid-fastness and that xylene treatment should be avoided when possible.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Fluorescent Auramine O staining, which targets intracellular nucleic acids, performed better than carbol fuchsin and may represent a superior option for histologic diagnosis of paucibacillary tuberculosis.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Auramine O and Ziehl–Neelsen stains are also useful for detecting intestinal coccidia, particularly *Cryptosporidium*, *Cystoisospora*, and *Cyclospora* species.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] These organisms exhibit partial or full acid-fastness, with oocysts appearing as bright yellow-green (auramine) or pink-red (Ziehl–Neelsen) structures against a contrasting background.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Screening of auramine-stained smears of fecal samples has been shown to markedly improve detection rates of coccidial infections in routine diagnostics, providing a rapid and inexpensive method suitable for large-scale screening programs.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] These findings are consistent with the broader interpretation that acid-fast stains act primarily as nucleic-acid stains whose retention depends on the integrity of the oocyst wall rather than lipid composition.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Ziehl–Neelsen staining is considered a narrow-spectrum fungal stain.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] In other words, it is selective in what kinds of fungi it stains, so it can help differentiate and identify fungi.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The results of Ziehl–Neelsen staining are variable because many fungal cell walls are not acid-fast.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] An example of a common type of acid-fast fungus that is usually stained with Ziehl–Neelsen staining is *Histoplasma*.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] *Histoplasma* is found in soil and the feces of birds and bats.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Humans can contract histoplasmosis by inhalation of the fungal spores.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] The yeast forms reach the bloodstream and may affect lymph nodes and other organs.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] More recently, acid-fast and fluorescent stains have been shown to highlight structures in the eggs of *Schistosoma* species.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Both Ziehl–Neelsen and auramine O staining demonstrate characteristic fluorescence or chromatic enhancement along the eggshell and within internal structures.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] This has diagnostic relevance, as it may assist in the recognition of eggs in stool and urine samples, particularly in low-intensity infections or after partial degradation.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Fluorescent staining with auramine O has been proposed as a rapid adjunct technique for screening schistosomiasis in endemic regions and differentiating species based on distinct staining patterns.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Earlier work had also demonstrated that Ziehl–Neelsen staining can highlight both the shell and species-specific internal features of schistosome eggs, supporting its diagnostic and taxonomic value.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] These findings, together with fluorescence studies on other acid-fast organisms, further support the interpretation that acid-fast stains primarily target nucleic acids and can reveal diagnostically relevant structures beyond bacteria.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] In 1882 Robert Koch discovered the etiology of tuberculosis.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Soon after Koch's discovery, Paul Ehrlich developed a stain for mycobacterium tuberculosis, called the alum hematoxylin stain.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Franz Ziehl then altered Ehrlich's staining technique by using carbolic acid as the mordant.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Friedrich Neelsen kept Ziehl's choice of mordant but changed the primary stain to carbol fuchsin.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Ziehl and Neelsen's modifications together have developed the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] Another acid-fast stain was developed by Joseph Kinyoun by using the Ziehl–Neelsen staining technique but removing the heating step from the procedure.
[src:gas-pak/acid-fast-stain] This new stain from Kinyoun was named the Kinyoun stain.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] An **agar plate** is a Petri dish that contains a growth medium solidified with agar, used to culture microorganisms.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Sometimes selective compounds are added to influence growth, such as antibiotics.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Individual microorganisms placed on the plate will grow into individual colonies, each a clone genetically identical to the individual ancestor organism (except for the low, unavoidable rate of mutation).
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Thus, the plate can be used either to estimate the concentration of organisms in a liquid culture or a suitable dilution of that culture using a colony counter, or to generate genetically pure cultures from a mixed culture of genetically different organisms.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Several methods are available to plate out cells.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] In this technique, a drop of the culture on the end of a thin, sterile loop of wire, sometimes known as an inoculator, is streaked across the surface of the agar leaving organisms behind, a higher number at the beginning of the streak and a lower number at the end.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] At some point during a successful "streak", the number of organisms deposited will be such that distinct individual colonies will grow in that area which may be removed for further culturing, using another sterile loop.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Another way of plating organisms, next to streaking, on agar plates is the spot analysis.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] This type of analysis is often used to check the viability of cells and is performed with pinners (often also called froggers).
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] A third technique is using sterile glass beads to plate out cells.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] In this technique, cells are grown in a liquid culture, in which a small volume is pipetted on the agar plate and then spread out with the beads.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Replica plating is another technique used to plate out cells on agar plates.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] These four techniques are the most common, but others are also possible.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] It is crucial to work in a sterile manner to prevent contamination on the agar plates.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Plating is thus often done in a laminar flow cabinet or on the working bench next to a bunsen burner.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] In 1881, Fanny Hesse, who was working as a technician for her husband Walther Hesse in the laboratory of Robert Koch, suggested agar as an effective setting agent, since it had been commonplace in jam making for some time.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Agar plates may be formulated as either permissive, with the intent of allowing the growth of whatever organisms are present, or restrictive or selective, with the intent of only allowing the growth of a particular subset of those organisms.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] This correlates to some degree with defined and undefined media; undefined media, made from natural products and containing an unknown combination of very many organic molecules, is typically more permissive in terms of supplying the needs of a wider variety of organisms.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] In contrast, defined media can be precisely tailored to select organisms with specific properties.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Agar plates may also be indicator plates, in which the organisms are not selected based on growth, but are instead distinguished by a color change in some colonies, typically caused by the action of an enzyme on some compound added to the medium.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] The plates are incubated for 12 hours up to several days, depending on the test that is performed.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Blood agar plates (BAPs) contain mammalian blood (usually sheep or horse), typically at a 5–10% concentration.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] BAPs are enriched, and differential media is used to isolate fastidious organisms and detect hemolytic activity. β-Hemolytic activity will show lysis and complete digestion of red blood cell contents surrounding a colony.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Examples include *Streptococcus haemolyticus*. α-Hemolysis will only cause partial lysis of the red blood cells (the cell membrane is left intact) and appear green or brown due to the conversion of hemoglobin to methemoglobin.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] An example of this would be *Streptococcus viridans*. γ-Hemolysis (or non-hemolytic) is the term referring to a lack of hemolytic activity.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] BAPs also contain meat extract or yeast extract, tryptone, sodium chloride, and agar.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Chocolate agar is a type of blood agar plate in which the blood cells have been lysed by heating the cells to 80 °C.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] It is used for growing fastidious respiratory bacteria, such as *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Chocolate agar is named for its color, and no chocolate is contained in the plate.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Thayer–Martin agar is a chocolate agar designed to isolate *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* and *Neisseria meningitidis*.
[src:gas-pak/agar-plate] Thiosulfate–citrate–bile salts–sucrose agar enhances growth of *Vibrio* spp., including *Vibrio cholerae*.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] A **hermetic seal** is any type of sealing that makes a given object **airtight** (preventing the passage of air, oxygen, or other gases).
[src:gas-pak/airtight] The term originally applied to airtight glass containers, but as technology advanced, it applied to a larger category of materials, including metals, and rubber.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Hermetic seals are essential to the correct and safe functionality of many electronic and healthcare products.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Used technically, the term is stated in conjunction with a specific test method and conditions of use.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Colloquially, the exact requirements of such a seal varies with the application.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] The word *hermetic* is indirectly related to the Greek god Hermes.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] The hermetic seal comes from alchemy in the tradition of Hermeticism, which was named after Hermes Trismegistus, a legendary figure who, according to the Hermeticists, invented the process of making a glass tube airtight using a secret seal.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Some kinds of packaging must maintain a seal against the flow of gases, for example, packaging for some foods, pharmaceuticals, chemicals, and consumer goods.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] The term can describe the result of some food preservation practices, such as vacuum packing and canning.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Packaging materials include glass, aluminum cans, metal foils, and gas-impermeable plastics.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Some buildings designed with sustainable architecture principles may use airtight technologies to conserve energy.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Green buildings may include windows that combine triple-pane insulated glazing with argon or krypton gas to reduce thermal conductivity and increase efficiency.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] In landscape and exterior construction projects, airtight seals may be used to protect general services and landscape lighting electrical connections/splices.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Airtight implies both waterproof and vapor-proof.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Hermetic seals enable human spaceflight by sealing breathable air in the habitable areas; without hermetic sealing, the air would expand and scatter to fill the near-vacuum of space, resulting in depressurization, which can cause injury or death in living organisms.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Airlocks, which rely on hermetic sealing technology, are used to allow things and organisms to enter and exit two areas with different pressures or compositions.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Airlocks are used in underwater diving, underground construction, mining, and spaceflight.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Electronic devices that use hermetic sealing include semiconductor electronics, thermostats, optical devices, MEMS, and switches.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Electrical or electronic parts may be hermetic sealed to secure against water vapor and foreign bodies to maintain proper functioning and reliability.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Hermetic sealing for airtight conditions is used in archiving significant historical items.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Bill of Rights were hermetically sealed with helium gas in glass cases housed in the U.S.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] In 2003, they were moved to new glass cases hermetically sealed with argon.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] In the funeral industry, some caskets and burial vaults are hermetically sealed by a rubber seal and being locked.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Typical epoxy resins have pendant hydroxyl (-OH) groups along their chain that can form bonds or strong polar attractions to oxide or hydroxyl surfaces.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Most inorganic surfaces—i.e., metals, minerals, glasses, ceramics—have polarity so they have high surface energy.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] The important factor in determining good adhesive strength is whether the surface energy of the substrate is close to or higher than the surface energy of the cured adhesive.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Certain epoxy resins and their processes can create a hermetic bond to copper, brass, stainless steel, specialty alloys, plastic, or epoxy itself with similar coefficients of thermal expansion, and are used in the manufacture of hermetic electrical and fiber optic hermetic seals.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Epoxy-based seals can increase signal density within a feedthrough design compared to other technologies with minimal spacing requirements between electrical conductors.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Epoxy hermetic seal designs can be used in hermetic seal applications for low or high vacuum or pressures, effectively sealing gases or fluids including helium gas to very low helium gas leak rates similar to glass or ceramic.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Hermetic epoxy seals also offer the design flexibility of sealing either copper alloy wires or pins instead of the much less electrically conductive Kovar pin materials required in glass or ceramic hermetic seals.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] With a typical operating temperature range of −70 °C to +125 °C or 150 °C, epoxy hermetic seals are more limited in comparison to glass or ceramic seals, although some hermetic epoxy designs are capable of withstanding 200 °C.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] When the glass and the metal being hermetically sealed have the same coefficient of thermal expansion, a "matched seal" derives its strength from bond between the glass and the metal's oxide.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] This type of glass-to-metal hermetic seal is generally used for low-intensity applications such as in light bulb bases.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] "Compression seals" occur when the glass and the metal have different coefficients of thermal expansion such that the metal compresses around the solidified glass as it cools.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Compression seals can withstand very high pressure and are used in a variety of industrial applications.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Compared to epoxy hermetic seals, glass-to-metal seals can be operated up to much higher temperatures (250 °C for compression seals, 450 °C for matched seals).
[src:gas-pak/airtight] The material selection is however more limited due to thermal expansion constraints.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] The sealing process is performed at roughly 1000 °C in an inert or reducing atmosphere to prevent discoloration of the parts.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Co-fired ceramic seals are an alternative to glass.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Ceramic seals exceed the design barriers of glass to metal seals due to superior hermetic performance in high stress environments requiring a robust seal.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Choosing between glass versus ceramic depends on the application, weight, thermal solution, and material requirements.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Glass taper joints can be sealed hermetically with PTFE sealing rings (high vacuum tight, air leakage rate 10−6 mBar × L/sec and below), o-rings (optionally encapsulated o-rings), or PTFE sleeves, sometimes used instead of grease that can dissolve into contamination.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] PTFE tape, PTFE resin string, and wax are other alternatives that are finding widespread use, but require a little care when winding onto the joint to ensure a good seal is produced.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] A thin layer of grease made for this application can be applied to the ground glass surfaces to be connected, and the inner joint is inserted into the outer joint such that the ground glass surfaces of each are next to each other to make the connection.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] In addition to making a leak-tight connection, the grease lets two joints be later separated more easily.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] A potential drawback of such grease is that if used on laboratory glassware for a long time in high-temperature applications (such as for continuous distillation), the grease may eventually contaminate the chemicals.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Also, reagents may react with the grease, especially under vacuum.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] For these reasons, it is advisable to apply a light ring of grease at the fat end of the taper and not its tip, to keep it from going inside the glassware.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] If the grease smears over the entire taper surface on mating, too much was used.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Ground glass joints are translucent when clean and free of debris.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Solvents, reaction mixtures, and old grease appear as transparent spots.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Grease can be removed by wiping with an appropriate solvent; ethers, methylene chloride, ethyl acetate, or hexanes work well for silicone- and hydrocarbon-based greases.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Fluoroether-based greases are quite impervious to organic solvents.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Most chemists simply wipe them off as much as possible.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Some fluorinated solvents can remove fluoroether greases, but are costlier than laboratory solvents.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Standard test methods are available for measuring the moisture vapor transmission rate, oxygen transmission rate, etc. of packaging materials.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] Completed packages, however, involve heat seals, joints, and closures that often reduce the effective barrier of the package.
[src:gas-pak/airtight] For example, the glass of a glass bottle may have an effective total barrier but the screw cap closure and the closure liner might not.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Corundum is the most common naturally occurring crystalline form of aluminium oxide.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Rubies and sapphires are gem-quality forms of corundum, which owe their characteristic colours to trace impurities.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Rubies are given their characteristic deep red colour and their laser qualities by traces of chromium.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Sapphires come in different colours given by various other impurities, such as iron and titanium.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] An extremely rare delta form occurs as the mineral deltalumite.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Although aluminium is the most abundant metal in the Earth's crust, it must be extracted from bauxite as alumina to produce aluminium metal.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The field of aluminium oxide ceramics has a long history.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium salts were widely used in ancient and medieval alchemy.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Several vintage textbooks cover the history of the field.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Al2O3 is an electrical insulator but has a relatively high thermal conductivity (30 Wm−1K−1) for a ceramic material.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In its most commonly occurring crystalline form, called corundum or α-aluminium oxide, its hardness makes it suitable for use as an abrasive and as a component in cutting tools.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is responsible for the resistance of metallic aluminium to weathering.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Metallic aluminium is very reactive with atmospheric oxygen, and a thin passivation layer of aluminium oxide (~5 nm thickness) forms on any exposed aluminium surface almost instantly.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] This layer protects the metal from further oxidation.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The thickness and properties of this oxide layer can be enhanced using a process called anodising.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] A number of alloys, such as aluminium bronzes, exploit this property by including a proportion of aluminium in the alloy to enhance corrosion resistance.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The aluminium oxide generated by anodising is typically amorphous, but discharge-assisted oxidation processes such as plasma electrolytic oxidation result in a significant proportion of crystalline aluminium oxide in the coating, enhancing its hardness.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide was taken off the United States Environmental Protection Agency's chemicals lists in 1988.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is on the EPA's Toxics Release Inventory list if it is a fibrous form.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is an amphoteric substance, meaning it can react with both acids and bases, such as hydrofluoric acid and sodium hydroxide, acting as an acid with a base and a base with an acid, neutralising the other and producing a salt.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The most common form of crystalline aluminium oxide is known as corundum, which is the thermodynamically stable form.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The oxygen ions form a nearly hexagonal close-packed structure with the aluminium ions filling two-thirds of the octahedral interstices.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In terms of its crystallography, corundum adopts a trigonal Bravais lattice with a space group of R3c (number 167 in the International Tables).
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The primitive cell contains two formula units of aluminium oxide.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide also exists in other metastable phases, including the cubic γ and η phases, the monoclinic λ, θ, θ', and θ″ phase, the hexagonal χ phase, the orthorhombic κ phase the orthorhombic δ phase and the δ' tetragonal phase.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Each has a unique crystal structure and properties.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Cubic γ-Al2O3 has important technical applications.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The so-called β-Al2O3 proved to be NaAl11O17.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Molten aluminium oxide near the melting temperature is roughly 2/3 tetrahedral (i.e.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] 2/3 of the Al are surrounded by 4 oxygen neighbors), and 1/3 5-coordinated, with very little (<5%) octahedral Al-O present.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Around 80% of the oxygen atoms are shared among three or more Al-O polyhedra, and the majority of inter-polyhedral connections are corner-sharing, with the remaining 10–20% being edge-sharing.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The breakdown of octahedra upon melting is accompanied by a relatively large volume increase (~33%), the density of the liquid close to its melting point is 2.93 g/cm3.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The structure of molten alumina is temperature dependent and the fraction of 5- and 6-fold aluminium increases during cooling (and supercooling), at the expense of tetrahedral AlO4 units, approaching the local structural arrangements found in amorphous alumina.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium hydroxide minerals are the main component of bauxite, the principal ore of aluminium.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] A mixture of the minerals comprise bauxite ore, including gibbsite (Al(OH)3), boehmite (γ-AlO(OH)), and diaspore (α-AlO(OH)), along with impurities of iron oxides and hydroxides, quartz and clay minerals.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Except for SiO2, the other components of bauxite do not dissolve in base.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Upon filtering the basic mixture, Fe2O3 is removed.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] When the Bayer liquor is cooled, Al(OH)3 precipitates, leaving the silicates in solution.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The product aluminium oxide tends to be multi-phase, i.e., consisting of several phases of aluminium oxide rather than solely corundum.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The production process can therefore be optimized to produce a tailored product.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The type of phases present affects, for example, the solubility and pore structure of the aluminium oxide product which, in turn, affects the cost of aluminium production and pollution control.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The Sintering Process is a high-temperature method primarily used when the Bayer Process is not suitable, especially for ores with high silica content or when a more controlled product morphology is required.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Firstly, Bauxite is mixed with additives like limestone and soda ash, then heating the mixture at high temperatures (1200 °C to 1500 °C) to form sodium aluminate and calcium silicate.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] After sintering, the material is leached with water to dissolve the sodium aluminate, leaving behind impurities.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Sodium aluminate is then precipitated from the solution and calcined at around 1000 °C to produce alumina.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] This method is useful for the production of complex shapes and can be used to create porous or dense materials.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Known as *alpha alumina* in materials science, and as *alundum* (in fused form) or *aloxite* in mining and ceramic communities, aluminium oxide finds wide use.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Annual global production of aluminium oxide in 2015 was approximately 115 million tonnes, over 90% of which was used in the manufacture of aluminium metal.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The major uses of speciality aluminium oxides are in refractories, ceramics, polishing and abrasive applications.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Large tonnages of aluminium hydroxide, from which alumina is derived, are used in the manufacture of zeolites, coating titania pigments, and as a fire retardant/smoke suppressant.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Over 90% of aluminium oxide, termed *smelter grade alumina* (SGA), is consumed for the production of aluminium, usually by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The remainder, termed *specialty alumina*, is used in a wide variety of applications which take advantage of its inertness, temperature resistance and electrical resistance.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Being fairly chemically inert and white, aluminium oxide is commonly used as a filler for plastics.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is a common ingredient in sunscreen and is often also present in cosmetics such as blush, lipstick, and nail polish.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Many formulations of glass have aluminium oxide as an ingredient.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminosilicate glass is a commonly used type of glass that often contains 5% to 10% alumina.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide catalyses a variety of reactions that are useful industrially.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In its largest scale application, aluminium oxide is the catalyst in the Claus process for converting hydrogen sulfide waste gases into elemental sulfur in refineries.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] It is also useful for dehydration of alcohols to alkenes.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide serves as a catalyst support for many industrial catalysts, such as those used in hydrodesulfurization and some Ziegler–Natta polymerizations.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is widely used to remove water from gas streams.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is used for its hardness and strength.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Its naturally occurring form, corundum, is a 9 on the Mohs scale of mineral hardness (just below diamond).
[src:gas-pak/alumina] It is widely used as an abrasive, including as a much less expensive substitute for industrial diamond.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Many types of sandpaper use aluminium oxide crystals.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In addition, its low heat retention and low specific heat make it widely used in grinding operations, particularly cutoff tools.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] As the powdery abrasive mineral aloxite, it is a major component, along with silica, of the cue tip "chalk" used in billiards.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide powder is used in some CD/DVD polishing and scratch-repair kits.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Its polishing qualities are also behind its use in toothpaste.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] It is also used in microdermabrasion, both in the machine process available through dermatologists and estheticians, and as a manual dermal abrasive used according to manufacturer directions.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide flakes are used in paint for reflective decorative effects, such as in the automotive or cosmetic industries.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is a representative of bioinert ceramics.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Due to its excellent biocompatibility, high strength, and wear resistance, alumina ceramics are used in medical applications to manufacture artificial bones and joints.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In this case, aluminium oxide is used to coat the surfaces of medical implants to give biocompatibility and corrosion resistance.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] It is also used for manufacturing dental implants, joint replacements, and other medical devices.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide has been used in a few experimental and commercial fiber materials for high-performance applications (e.g., Fiber FP, Nextel 610, Nextel 720).
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Alumina nanofibers in particular have become a research field of interest.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Some body armor utilizes alumina ceramic plates, usually in combination with aramid or UHMWPE backing to achieve effectiveness against most rifle threats.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Alumina ceramic armor is readily available to most civilians in jurisdictions where it is legal, but it is not considered military grade.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] An aluminium oxide layer can be grown as a protective coating on aluminium by anodizing or by plasma electrolytic oxidation (see the "Properties" above).
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Alumina is used to manufacture tiles which are attached inside pulverized fuel lines and flue gas ducting on coal fired power stations to protect high wear areas.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] They are not suitable for areas with high impact forces as these tiles are brittle and susceptible to breakage.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The Al2O3 films prepared using O3 show 10–100 times lower leakage current density compared with those prepared by H2O.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide, being a dielectric with relatively large band gap, is used as an insulating barrier in capacitors.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium ice cream scoops, if improperly washed by using a dishwasher rather than washed by hand, can corrode and leave an aluminium oxide residue, which can present a health concern.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In lighting, translucent aluminium oxide is used in some sodium vapor lamps.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is also used in preparation of coating suspensions in compact fluorescent lamps.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In chemistry laboratories, aluminium oxide is a medium for chromatography, available in basic (pH 9.5), acidic (pH 4.5 when in water), and neutral formulations.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Additionally, small pieces of aluminium oxide are often used as boiling chips.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Health and medical applications include it as a material in hip replacements and birth-control pills.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] It is used as a scintillator and dosimeter for radiation protection and therapy applications for its optically stimulated luminescence properties.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Insulation for high-temperature furnaces is often manufactured from aluminium oxide.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Sometimes the insulation contains a percentage of silica depending on the temperature rating of the material.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] The insulation can be made in blanket, board, brick, and loose fiber forms for various application requirements.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] It is also used to make spark-plug insulators.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Using a plasma-spray process and mixed with titania, it is coated onto the braking surface of some bicycle rims to provide abrasion and wear resistance.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Most ceramic eyes on fishing rods are circular rings made from aluminium oxide.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] In its finest powdered (white) form, called diamantine, aluminium oxide is used as a superior polishing abrasive in watchmaking and clockmaking.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] Aluminium oxide is also used in the coating of stanchions in the motocross and mountain-bike industries.
[src:gas-pak/alumina] This coating is combined with molybdenum disulfide to provide long-term lubrication of the surface.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] An **anaerobic organism** or **anaerobe** is any organism that does not require molecular oxygen for its growth.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] It may react negatively or even die in the presence of free oxygen.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Anaerobic organisms do not use oxygen as a terminal electron acceptor in their respiration process to produce energy, but a less powerful oxidizing agent, such as nitrate, ferric ion, Mn(IV), sulfate or bicarbonate anions.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] In contrast, an aerobic organism (aerobe) is an organism that requires a sufficiently oxygenated environment to respire, produce its energy, and thrive.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] However, a minuscule multicellular organism, with an exceptionally rare metabolism and surviving in a hypersaline brine pool in the darkness of the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea, has been recently discovered.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Meanwhile, it remains a scientific curiosity, as the much higher energy requirements of most multicellular organisms cannot be met by anaerobic respiration.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The deep seafloor and its underlying unconsolidated sediments ranks among the largest potential habitats for anaerobic microorganisms on Earth.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Moreover, chemoautotroph microbes also thrive around hydrothermal vents, discharging hot water on the ocean seabed near mid-ocean ridges, where anaerobic conditions prevail.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] These microbes produce energy in the absence of sunlight or oxygen through a process called anaerobic respiration, whereby inorganic compounds and ions such as protons (H+), elemental sulfur and its derivatives (SO2−4, S2O2−3), or ferric ions, are reduced to drive oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] In his 14 June 1680 letter to the Royal Society, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek described an experiment he carried out by filling two identical glass tubes about halfway with crushed pepper powder, to which some clean rain water was added.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Van Leeuwenhoek sealed one of the glass tubes with a flame and left the other open.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] In 1913, Martinus Beijerinck repeated Van Leeuwenhoek's experiment and identified *Clostridium butyricum* as a prominent anaerobic bacterium in the sealed pepper infusion tube liquid.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Some obligate anaerobes use fermentation, while others use anaerobic respiration.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Aerotolerant organisms are strictly fermentative.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] In the presence of oxygen, facultative anaerobes use aerobic respiration.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] In the absence of oxygen, some facultative anaerobes use fermentation, while others may use anaerobic respiration.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] There are many anaerobic fermentative reactions.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The energy released in this reaction (without ADP and phosphate) is approximately 150 kJ per mol, which is conserved in generating two ATP from ADP per glucose.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] This is only 5% of the energy per sugar molecule that the typical aerobic reaction generates.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The energy released is about 180 kJ/mol, which is conserved when 2 ATP are generated from 2 ADP per glucose.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Anaerobic bacteria and archaea use these and many other fermentative pathways, e.g., propionic acid fermentation, butyric acid fermentation, solvent fermentation, mixed acid fermentation, butanediol fermentation, Stickland fermentation, acetogenesis, or methanogenesis.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Creatine, an organic compound found in animals, provides a way for ATP to be utilized in the muscle.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The phosphorylation of creatine allows for the storage of readily available phosphate that can be supplied to the muscles.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The reaction is reversible as well, allowing cellular ATP levels to be maintained during anoxic conditions.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] This process in animals is seen to be coupled with metabolic suppression to allow certain fish, such as goldfish, to survive environmental anoxic conditions for a short period.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Since normal microbial culturing is done in atmospheric air, which contains molecular oxygen, culturing anaerobes requires special techniques.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The Gas-pak System is an isolated container that achieves an anaerobic environment by the reaction of water with sodium borohydride and sodium bicarbonate tablets, which produce hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Hydrogen then reacts with oxygen gas on a palladium catalyst to produce more water, thereby removing oxygen gas.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The issue with the Gas-Pak method is that an adverse reaction can occur, leading to bacterial death; therefore, a thioglycolate medium should be used.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The thioglycolate supplies a medium mimicking that of a dicot plant, thus providing not only an anaerobic environment but all the nutrients needed for the bacteria to multiply.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] On May the 6 2018, a French team evidenced a link between redox and gut anaerobes based on clinical studies of severe acute malnutrition.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] These findings led to the development of an aerobic culture of "anaerobes" by the addition of antioxidants in the culture medium.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Very few multicellular life forms are anaerobic, since only aerobic respiration can provide enough energy for a complex metabolism.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Exceptions include three species of *Loricifera* (< 1 mm in size) and the 10-cell *Henneguya zschokkei*.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] In 2010, three species of anaerobic *Loricifera* were discovered in the hypersaline anoxic L'Atalante basin at the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] They lack mitochondria, which contain the oxidative phosphorylation pathway, which in all other animals combines oxygen with glucose to produce metabolic energy; thus, they consume no oxygen.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Instead, these *loricifera* derive their energy from hydrogen, using hydrogenosomes.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Anaerobic respiration and its end products can facilitate symbiosis between anaerobes and aerobes.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] This occurs across taxa, often in compensation for nutritional needs.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Anaerobiosis and symbiosis are found in interactions between ciliates and prokaryotes.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Anaerobic ciliates interact with prokaryotes in an endosymbiotic relationship.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] These relationships are mediated in which the ciliate leaves end products that its prokaryotic symbiont utilizes.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The ciliate achieves this through fermentative metabolism.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The rumen of various animals houses this ciliate alongside many other anaerobic bacteria, protozoans, and fungi.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] In specific, methanogenic archaea found in the rumen acts as a symbiont to anaerobic ciliates.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] These anaerobes are useful to those with a rumen due to their ability to break down cellulose, making it bioavailable when otherwise indigestible by animals.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Termites utilize anaerobic bacteria to fix and recapture nitrogen.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Specifically, the termite's hindgut is full of nitrogen-fixing bacteria, whose functions depend on the nitrogen concentration of the diet.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] Acetylene reduction in termites was observed to upregulate in termites with nitrogen-poor diets, meaning that nitrogenase activity rose as the nitrogen content of the termite was reduced.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] One of the functions of termite microbiota is to recapture nitrogen from the termite's uric acid.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] This allows nitrogen conservation from a diet otherwise low in nitrogen.
[src:gas-pak/anaerobes] The hindgut microbiome of different termites has been analyzed, showing 16 different anaerobic species of bacteria, including Clostridia, Enterobacteriaceae, and Gram-positive cocci.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] The **analytical profile index**, or **API**, is a classification system for bacteria based on biochemical tests.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] The system was developed to accelerate the speed of identifying clinically relevant bacteria.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] It can only be used to identify known species from an index.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] The data obtained are phenotypic traits.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] DNA sequence-based methods, including multi-locus sequence typing and even whole-genome sequencing, are increasingly used in the identification of bacterial species and strains.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] These newer methods can be used to complement or even replace the use of API testing in clinical settings.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] The analytical profile index (API) was invented in the 1970s in the United States by Pierre Janin of Analytab Products Inc.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] The API test system is currently manufactured by bioMérieux.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] The API range introduced a standardized and miniaturized version of existing techniques, which were considered complicated to perform and difficult to read.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] Identification is only possible with a microbiological culture.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] API test strips consist of wells containing dehydrated substrates such as the redox substrates, electrogenic substrates and luminogenic substrates to detect enzymatic activity, usually related to the fermentation of carbohydrate or catabolism of proteins or amino acids by the inoculated organisms.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] A bacterial suspension is used to rehydrate each of the wells and the strips are incubated.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] During incubation, metabolism produces color changes that are either spontaneous or revealed by the addition of reagents.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] For example, when carbohydrates are fermented, the pH within the well decreases and that is indicated by a change in the color of the pH indicator.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] All test results are compiled to obtain a profile number, which is then compared with profile numbers in a commercial codebook (or online) to determine the identification of the bacterial species.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] Before starting a test, one must confirm the cultured bacteria are Enterobacteriaceae, this is done by a quick oxidase test for cytochrome coxidase.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] Enterobacteriaceae are typically oxidase negative, meaning they either do not use oxygen as an electron acceptor in the electron transport chain, or they use a different cytochrome enzyme for transferring electrons to oxygen.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] If the culture is determined to be oxidase-positive, alternative tests must be carried out to correctly identify the bacterial species.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] API-20E is specific for differentiating between members of the Gram-negative bacteria family Enterobacteriaceae.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] Another API system, API-Staph, is specific for Gram-positive bacteria, including *Staphylococcus* species, *Micrococcus* species, and related organisms.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] The **API 20E/NE** system is a widely used biochemical test system designed for the rapid identification of Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] It specifically targets two groups: Enterobacteriaceae (API 20E) and non-Enterobacteriaceae (API 20NE).
[src:gas-pak/analytical-profile-index] This system is particularly useful in clinical microbiology and environmental studies for identifying bacteria based on their biochemical activities.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] These are commercially available, disposable sachets containing a dry powder or pellets, which, when mixed with water and kept in an appropriately sized airtight jar, produce an atmosphere free of elemental oxygen gas (O2).
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] They are used to produce an anaerobic culture in microbiology.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] It is a much simpler technique than the McIntosh and Filde's anaerobic jar where one needs to pump gases in and out.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] The addition of a Dicot Catalyst may be required to initiate the reaction.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] These chemicals react with water to produce hydrogen and carbon dioxide along with sodium citrate (C3H5O(COONa)3) and water as byproducts [1].
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] Again, hydrogen and oxygen reacting on a catalyst like Palladiumised alumina (supplied separately) combine to form water.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] The medium, the gas-pak sachet (opened and with water added) and an indicator are placed in an air-tight gas jar which is incubated at the desired temperature.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] The indicator tells whether the environment was indeed oxygen free or not.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] The chemical indicator generally used for this purpose is "chemical methylene blue solution" that since synthesis has never been exposed to elemental oxygen.
[src:gas-pak/gas-pak] It is colored deep blue on oxidation in presence of atmospheric oxygen in the jar, but will become colorless when oxygen is gone, and anaerobic conditions are achieved.
